@Jane Wheelaghan

In American football, the quarterback calls out a series of signals as the play is about to begin. HUT is usually a signal word to start the play.  It has to be coordinated like a conductor leads an orchestra, because if anyone starts before the ball is snapped (handed off to the quarterback), it is a foul and carries a five-yard penalty.

Why does he say HUT?  It was originally "hike," which is the term for handing the ball to the quarterback, but HUT is easier to say with a mouthguard on.

